## Deferred vs In-Frame Entity Operations

| Operation | When applied | Set required | Visibility |
|---|---|---|---|
| `emplace_deferred` | End of current frame | `addSet` | Next frame |
| `emplace_oneframe` | End of current frame, removed end of next flush | `addSet` | Exactly one frame |
| `EmplaceEvent` | End of current frame, destroyed next frame after consumption | `addSet` | Next frame, one frame only |
| `emplace_inframe` | Immediately (synchronous) | `inframeAddSet` | Same frame (later systems only) |
| `EmplaceInframeEvent` | Immediately (synchronous) | `inframeAddSet` | Same frame (later systems only), destroyed at frame end |
| `EmplaceExternalEvent` | End of current frame | none (external) | Next frame |
| `remove_deferred` | End of current frame | none | Removed next frame |
| `destroy_deferred` | End of current frame (after emplaces) | none | Destroyed next frame |

**Why deferred?**

EnTT invalidates active views and iterators when the registry is structurally modified (entity created/destroyed, component added/removed). Systems iterate views during `Update()`. If a system could immediately add a component during its own iteration, it would corrupt the view iterator. The deferred buffer guarantees that all structural changes are batched and applied in a single safe window after all systems have finished iterating.

**Why in-frame (`inframeAddSet`)?**

Some workflows require the data to be available to downstream systems within the same frame, not deferred to the next. The canonical case is render command dispatch: a UI/scene system creates `DrawQuadInFrameEvent` entities that the renderer system (which runs later in the same frame, enforced by topological sort) reads and consumes. Because the producer finishes its view iteration before calling `EmplaceInframeEvent`, no iterator corruption occurs.

